summary.seg:
This manuscript contains a part (books 1-4) of the Commentary to Plato's Parmenides by Proclus. It was copied in 1695 from Oxford, Bodleian Library, Auct. F.3.23 (Misc. gr. 97) by the librarian and antiquary Humfrey Wanley (1672-1726), later librarian of Robert Harley, Earl of Oxford, and of his son Edward. The copy had been commissioned by the Cambridge scholar and antiquarian Thomas Gale. Within the manuscript has been bound a letter from Wanley to Gale ( f. [iv]): Wanley informed him that he had completed his work, and that the task required him much more that he had expected, and asked therefore for £2 more than the agreed remuneration of £4. The letter informs us also that this was the first Greek manuscript copied by Humfrey Wanley. A payment receipt, also bound into the manuscript ( f. [v]), shows that the request was not accepted by Gale. Two years later, Thomas Gale had the remaining books of the commentary, 5-7, copied by an anonymous scribe, which copy is now Trinity College, MS O.5.11 , which was transcribed from what is now
Paris, Bibliothèque Nationale de France, gr. 1836.
Another letter to Gale bound in the manuscript ( f. [vi]) also attests to his keen interest in Proclus: it is a letter from John Mill, who was engaged in collating Proclus.

support.material:
Western paper, folded in folio. Watermarks: ff. [vii]-[xi] Coat of arms with a shield on which there are three X, flanked by two rampant lions and surmounted by a crown surmounted by a globe, with countermark W I
( 95 90 ) in the centre of the leaf, no exact parallels found in the main repertoires, but the watermark is comparable to the types Heawood Coat of arms 424, 428 , which are dated to 1667, 1678.
f. [xii] Coat of arms, a shield surmounted by a clover, divided in four, with a sword in one field ( 60 43 ) in the centre of the leaf, comparable to Heawood Coat of arms 454 , which is dated to 1700, but it is not possible to ascertain whether the watermark had a countermark.
ff. [i]-[iii], [xviii]-[xix] Pro Patria with countermark G R surmounted by a crown in circle ( 104 95 ) in the centre of the leaf, comparable (but the countermark is different) to Heawood Pro Patria 3700 , which is dated to 1747 (England).

foliation.p:
Pagination in brown ink, in Arabic numerals, in the upper margin right from 1 to 312. There are several unnumbered leaves:
ff. [i]-[iii] and [xviii]-[xix] are later andleaves, which came with the binding (see Watermarks)
ff. [vii]-[xi], [xiii]-[xvii] are blank unnumbered leaves
f. [xii] contains another copy of the beginning of the text by the scribe
ff. [iv], [v] and [vi] are two letters and a receipt bound in the manuscript. Ff. [i]-[iii] + [iv], [v], [vi] + [vii]-[xii] + pp. 1-22, [23], 24-312 + [xiii]-[xix]

The scribe added running titles, writing in the upper left corner of the verso of the leaves the word βιβλίον in majuscule letters, and in the upper right corner of the recto the number of the book of the commentary, Α / Β / Γ / Δ.

collation.p: The quires have been sewn tightly and are not numbered; it was not possible to assess the collation with certainty.

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript is in fair condition. The binding is completely detached from the text-block in the left part. Only a vertical strip of paper remains of the first endleaf, f. [i], the bifolium formed by ff. [i]-[ii] is almost completely detached from the book-block, f. [iii] is detached. The leaves have not been trimmed, and are yellowed throughout. There are a few ink stains.

layoutDesc.layout: A single column of 26 lines. Lines are traced in pencil, bounding lines are traced in red. 255 155

handNote.p: f. [xii] recto-[xii] verso, pp. 1-22, 24-173, 175-312 Hand A: the manuscript was copied by Humfrey Wanley (1672-1726) Wanley, Humphrey, 1672-1726 in a minuscule script slanting slightly to the right. The scribe signed the copy in 1695.
The text is written in brown ink

decoDesc.decoNote:
At the beginning of each book or chapter, there are pen flourished headpieces, in brown ink:
a vegetal motif of flowers and scrolls, at the centre a scroll with a human face, at its sides two circles containing the indication of the exemplar used by the scribe, and his colophon on p. 1
scrolling ornament with flowers and fruits on pp. 32, 129
rinceaux on p. 175.

Pen flourished initials traced with the same ink used for the text, decorated with an elaborated vegetal motif, see e.g. pp. 1, 32, 129. On p. 175 there are two champ initials, the background is formed by a vegetal decoration.

At the end of the books the scribe traced in ink some well executed drawings, depicting:
p. 31 a bowl of fruit
p. 128 a vase of flowers
p. 173 a ribbon (with chiaroscuro effects) on which has been written a final rubric. On p. 312 the space remaining on the leaf after the end of the text is filled with rinceaux.

additions.p: On the left pastedown is pasted a paper label with a note about the text: Scripsit in Parmenidem | Marinus vide Suidam in | Damascius, and, below, the shelfmark O.5.10.
On f. [vii] recto are written the present shelmark, O.5.10, and the note Vol. primum (in MS Trinity O.5.11 there is a corresponding note, Vol. secundum) and an older shelfmark, A. 10.

binding.p: Modern binding, paper cover over pasteboards; parchment on spine, where are glued three paper labels with the shelfmark O.5.10. 340 220 38
binding.condition: The cover is damaged and yellowed; the spine is damaged at the upper end. The left board and the spine are detached from the book-block.

accMat.p:
At the beginning of the codex, after f. [iii], have been bound three paper leaves:
f. [iv] ( 195 170 ) is a letter from Humfrey Wanley to Thomas Gale, dated on 7th November 1695, in Edmund Hall, Oxford; Wanley announces the completion of the transcript and asks for £2 more than the £4 agreed upon
f. [v] ( 80 130-140 ) is a receipt of the Carrier Th. Bartlett, dated on 15th November 1695, for £4 to be conveyed to Wanley (whose request had therefore not been accepted)
f. [vi] ( 180 300 ) is a letter from John Mill, who was engaged in collating Proclus, to Thomas Gale; the letter was sent to his house in London; on the exterior of the letter the seal is still preserved.

origin.p: The manuscript was copied by Humfrey Wanley in 1695, in Oxford, as stated in the colophon on p. 1, and also in a letter bound in the manuscript ( f. [iv]) written by him to Thomas Gale on 7th November 1695 from St. Edmund Hall (Oxford). The copy was commissioned by Thomas Gale (ca. 1635-1702) Gale, Thomas, 1635?-1702 , Regius professor of Greek at the University of Cambridge, High Master of St Paul's School and Dean of York.

history.acquisition:
It was donated to the library by Roger Gale (1672-1744) Gale, Roger, 1672-1744
in 1738. On ff. [vii] verso is pasted the Trinity College bookplate. On p. 312 there are stamps of Trinity College Library.

recordHist.source: Description (2020) draws partly on M.R. James, The Western Manuscripts in the Library of Trinity College Cambridge (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1902), vol. 3, p. 314.
